26/10/2007
ANKARA, Turkey -- Foreign ministers of countries in the Black Sea Economic Co-operation kicked off a meeting in Ankara on Thursday (October 25th).
In his opening speech, Turkish Foreign Minister Ali Babacan said that the link between terrorism and organised crime poses the largest threat to both regional and world security.
Insisting that the determined fight against those two phenomena is the obligation of the entire international community, he called for the drafting of a new global strategy against terrorism.
Turkish President Abdullah Gul also spoke at the forum, defending Turkey's right to fight terrorists from the Kurdistan Workers Party based in northern Iraq.
On the sidelines of the meeting, he met with Greek Foreign Minister Dora Bakoyannis about boosting bilateral ties.
(Milliyet - 26/10/07;
ANA-MPA, Sky - 25/10/07)
